Johannesburg - The Directorate for Priority Crimes (Hawks) has arrested three Tshwane University of Technology (TUT) students on charges of corruption.In a statement released on Wednesday, spokesperson for the Hawks, Brigadier Hangwani Mulaudzi, said the trio would make their first court appearance at the Specialised Commercial Crime Court in Pretoria on Thursday.The suspects, aged between 25 and 30, were arrested in Pretoria on Tuesday.&#x201C;The suspects, one of whom is a serving member of the Student Representative Council and two former TUT students allegedly demanded R100 000 from a security company owner in exchange for having the company&apos;s contract extended by the institution.The National Anti-Corruption Investigation Unit and Crime Intelligence got hold of the information and an undercover operation was instituted,&#x201D; Mulaudzi said. Police nabbed the suspects shortly after they received R40,000 in payment. African News Agency